   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,848:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,850:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | | Backtest-Calibration Loop | Iterative prediction validation and
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,852:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: parameter tuning |
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,853:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,855:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | | Full Lifecycle Automation | Discover -> simulate -> report -> remediate -> validate |
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,856:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,858:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | | Inverse
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,859:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Optimizer | Target SLA -> required changes computation |
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,882:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Each engine operates on the same in-memory directed graph representation described in Section 4.2, enabling
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,892:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: unified analysis across all methodologies. The multi-engine consensus pipeline (Section 4.7, Integration Pipelines)
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,894:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: combines results from multiple engines through voting, computing agreement scores with divergence detection.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,895:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 4.8 Resilience Score Computation
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,909:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The system aggregates simulation results into a quantitative resilience score (0-100) enabling comparison across
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,912:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: different infrastructure designs. The score integrates cascade severity distribution, SPOF count, availability layer
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,914:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: analysis, and redundancy coverage.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,915:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5. ALTERNATIVE EMBODIMENTS AND EXTENSIONS
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,917:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5.1 Machine Learning-Enhanced Scenario Generation
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,962:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: In an alternative embodiment, the automated scenario generator is augmented with a machine learning model
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,987:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (including but not limited to large language models, graph neural networks, or reinforcement learning agents) that
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,997:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: analyzes historical incident data, identifies failure combinations that are statistically likely but not covered by
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:00,999:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: rule-based generation, learns from simulation results to prioritize high-impact scenarios, and generates novel failure
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,000:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: scenarios.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,001:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5.2 Digital Twin Continuous Synchronization
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,041:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: In an alternative embodiment, the in-memory topology model is continuously synchronized with a real infrastructure
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,065:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: environment through real-time metric ingestion, automatic topology updates when changes are detected, continuous
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,076:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: simulation re-evaluation, and drift detection. A further refinement feeds the metric stream to a dependency inference
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,078:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: engine that discovers emergent relationships not present in the original topology declaration.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,079:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5.3 Natural Language Infrastructure Definition
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,086:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: In an alternative embodiment, the infrastructure topology is defined through natural language input, where a
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,088:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: language model interprets descriptions and automatically generates the corresponding graph topology.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,089:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5.4 Simulation-Driven Infrastructure Remediation
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,098:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: In an alternative embodiment, the system automatically generates Infrastructure-as-Code modifications from
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,100:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: simulation results, ranked by cost-effectiveness, and applies approved remediations through pull request generation.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,101:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5.5 Multi-Cloud Correlated Failure Analysis
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,105:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: In an alternative embodiment, the system models infrastructure spanning multiple cloud providers and analyzes
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,106:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: correlated failures across provider boundaries.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,107:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5.6 Cost-Constrained Resilience Optimization
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,114:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: In an alternative embodiment, the system performs multi-objective optimization to find optimal configurations under
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,115:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: cost constraints, including Pareto frontier computation and budget allocation optimization.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,116:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 6. CLAIMS
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,116:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Independent Claims
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,117:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Claim 1.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,118:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  A computer-implemented method for evaluating infrastructure resilience, comprising:
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,119:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,154:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (a) constructing, in computer memory, a directed graph representation of an infrastructure topology,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,175:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: wherein nodes represent infrastructure components annotated with component attributes including at
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,184:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: least component type, replica count, MTBF, MTTR, and operational profile, and edges represent
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,187:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: typed dependency relationships between components, each edge classified as one of required,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,189:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: optional, or asynchronous;
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,190:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,218:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (b) simulating failure propagation entirely in computer memory without affecting any real
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,231:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: infrastructure, using a formally-defined labeled transition system comprising a state tuple of (health
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,236:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: map, latency map, elapsed time, visited set) and typed transition rules that differentiate propagation
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,237:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: behavior based on dependency type, wherein:
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,237:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,240:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: required dependencies propagate failures unconditionally from a failed component
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,241:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: to its single-replica dependents,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,242:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,244:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: optional dependencies degrade performance of dependent components without
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,245:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: further cascade propagation,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,246:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,248:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: asynchronous dependencies propagate degradation with configurable delay
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,249:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: reflecting queue buildup behavior;
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,250:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,371:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (c) computing per-layer availability ceilings across at least five independent constraint layers — a
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,455:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: hardware layer computing single-instance availability from MTBF and MTTR with parallel
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,517:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: redundancy, a software layer accounting for deployment downtime and human error rate, a
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,558:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: theoretical layer computing the irreducible physical noise floor from packet loss and garbage
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,582:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: collection pauses, an operational layer modeling human factor availability from incident frequency
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,593:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: and response time, and an external SLA layer computing a hard ceiling from third-party service
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,597:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: availability — and determining the binding constraint layer as the layer producing the minimum
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,598:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: availability ceiling;
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,599:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,617:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (d) constraining the simulation results of step (b) by said per-layer ceilings of step (c), wherein a
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,624:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: simulation-predicted availability exceeding any layer ceiling triggers an indication that the result is
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,626:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: exceeding the computed availability ceiling and identifies the binding constraint layer;
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,626:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,638:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: (e) generating an infrastructure modification specification identifying specific changes to component
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,640:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: attributes in the directed graph that would relax the binding constraint layer, thereby enabling higher
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,641:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: achievable system availability;
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,642:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,693:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: wherein the method enables exhaustive combinatorial failure scenario analysis that is physically
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,724:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: impossible with real-environment fault injection due to the exponential growth of failure
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,742:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: combinations, and wherein a visited-set mechanism in the labeled transition system guarantees
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,748:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: simulation termination in O(|C| + |E|) time for acyclic dependency graphs where |C| is the number of
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,749:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: components and |E| is the number of dependency edges.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,750:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Claim 2.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:01,752:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  A computer-implemented method for simulating AI agent failure behavior as a function of infrastructure
