   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,089:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  The method of Claim 1, further comprising simulating latency cascade propagation through the
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,115:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: dependency graph by tracking accumulated latency through each dependency hop, evaluating circuit breaker
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,126:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: thresholds at each edge, computing connection pool exhaustion when accumulated latency causes request pileup,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,130:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: modeling retry storms as connection multiplication factors, and modeling singleflight request coalescing as a load
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,131:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: reduction factor.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,132:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Claim 10.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,182:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  The method of Claim 1, further comprising simulating autoscaling response to failure conditions by
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,213:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: modeling horizontal pod autoscaler (HPA) and event-driven autoscaler (KEDA) configurations, including minimum
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,228:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: and maximum replica counts, scaling thresholds, scale-up and scale-down delays, and step size, and computing the
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,233:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: time-dependent replica count during failure propagation to determine whether autoscaling can mitigate cascade
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,234:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: effects before they propagate to dependent components.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,235:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Claim 11.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,302:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  The method of Claim 1, further comprising performing what-if parameter sweep analysis by
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,347:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: systematically varying component attributes including replica counts, MTBF values, timeout thresholds, and circuit
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,370:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: breaker configurations across a defined parameter space, executing the failure simulation of step (b) and the
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,378:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: availability computation of step (c) for each parameter combination, and identifying the parameter changes that
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,379:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: produce the largest improvement in resilience score per unit of infrastructure cost.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,380:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Claim 12.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,402:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  The method of Claim 1, embodied as a system comprising: at least one processor; a memory coupled to
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,408:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: the at least one processor; and instructions stored in the memory that, when executed by the at least one processor,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,409:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: cause the system to perform the method of Claim 1.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,410:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Claim 13.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,415:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  The method of Claim 2, wherein the hallucination probability H for an AI agent a is computed using the
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,416:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: formula: for each unavailable data source d, h
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,417:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,417:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: d = h
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,418:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,418:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 0(a) + (1 - h
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,419:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,419:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 0(a)) 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,420:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: *
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,421:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  w(d), where h
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,421:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,425:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 0(a) is the base
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,426:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: hallucination rate and w(d) is the dependency weight; and H = 1 - product(1 - h
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,427:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,428:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: d) for all unavailable data sources.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,429:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: APPENDIX A: Prior Art Differentiation
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,430:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: A.1 Detailed Prior Art Comparison
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,431:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Krasnovsky 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,432:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: &
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,433:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  Zorkin (Connectivity-Based Resilience Model):
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,433:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:03,762:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Krasnovsky and Zorkin model infrastructure
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,070:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: resilience using graph connectivity metrics — vertex connectivity and edge connectivity — to measure how many
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,316:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: components or links must fail before a system becomes disconnected. Their model treats all dependencies as
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,519:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: equivalent graph edges, computes static connectivity metrics, and does not simulate dynamic failure cascade
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,679:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: behavior. The present invention differs fundamentally: (i) the cascade engine uses a formally-defined Labeled
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,809:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Transition System with eight typed transition rules, not connectivity metrics; (ii) dependency types (required,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,896:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: optional, asynchronous) produce qualitatively different propagation behaviors — required dependencies cascade
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,944:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: unconditionally while optional and asynchronous dependencies attenuate; (iii) circuit breaker containment modeling
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,970:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: halts cascade through protected paths; (iv) the LTS state tuple tracks health maps, latency maps, elapsed time, and
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,981:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: visited sets, enabling dynamic simulation of cascade propagation through time; (v) the system integrates multi-layer
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,984:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: availability constraints and AI agent failure modeling, neither of which is addressed by connectivity-based
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,985:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: approaches.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,987:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: GMOR (2016) (Generalized Multi-Hazard Outage Risk):
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:04,988:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,066:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: GMOR models physical infrastructure (power grids,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,124:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: water systems) exposure to natural hazards using fragility curves and Monte Carlo simulation. It analyzes physical
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,158:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: damage propagation through infrastructure networks but does not model IT infrastructure dependency types, does
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,176:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: not distinguish between required/optional/asynchronous software dependencies, does not incorporate circuit breaker
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,182:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: containment or timeout-based cascade, and has no AI agent behavior modeling. The present invention operates in
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,183:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: the IT infrastructure domain with software-specific dependency semantics.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,185:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Dell US11356324B2 (Graph Analysis for Fault Injection Target Selection):
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,185:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,186:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Dell
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,187:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,278:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: s patent describes a system that
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,351:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: analyzes infrastructure topology graphs to select optimal targets for real-environment fault injection. The graph
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,400:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: analysis is used for target prioritization, not for in-memory failure simulation. After targets are selected, faults are
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,428:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: injected into actual infrastructure. The present invention performs complete failure simulation entirely in memory
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,441:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: without affecting real infrastructure, simulates cascade propagation dynamics using formal LTS semantics,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,443:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: computes multi-layer availability ceilings, and models AI agent failure behavior — none of which is addressed by Dell
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,444:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,445:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: s
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,446:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: target selection system.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,447:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: agent-chaos/balagan-agent (AI Agent Chaos Engineering):
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,448:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,558:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: This tool injects real faults into AI agent
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,656:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: environments to observe agent failure behavior. It operates by actually disrupting agent infrastructure — modifying API
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,715:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: endpoints, injecting latency, restricting access to tools. The present invention does not inject real faults; it models
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,751:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: hallucination probability H(a, D, I) as a computable function of infrastructure state entirely in memory, enabling
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,770:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: exhaustive evaluation of failure combinations without risking real agent operation. The hallucination probability
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,776:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: model — connecting infrastructure health states to agent behavioral degradation through formal mathematical functions
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,777:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: — is not present in any real-fault-injection approach.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,779:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Isograph Reliability Workbench (Single-Layer Availability):
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,780:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,842:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Isograph and similar RAMS tools compute
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,893:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: availability using hardware reliability models (MTBF/MTTR with redundancy). They operate within a single
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,922:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: constraint layer. The present invention computes independent availability ceilings across five or more constraint
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,937:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: layers (hardware, software, theoretical, operational, external SLA), identifies the binding constraint layer, and
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,943:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: generates infrastructure modification specifications targeting that specific layer — a multi-layer constraint analysis
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,944:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: absent from single-layer reliability tools.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,945:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: AWS Fault Injection Service (FIS):
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,946:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,946:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: AWS
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:05,947:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,128:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: s managed fault injection service enables controlled experiments on
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,269:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: AWS infrastructure. FIS injects real faults (CPU stress, network disruption, instance termination) into actual running
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,368:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: AWS resources. FIS differs from the present invention in that: (1) FIS requires real infrastructure — experiments
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,428:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: execute against production or staging environments, incurring production risk; (2) FIS does not construct a formal
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,466:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: graph model of dependencies or simulate cascade propagation in-memory; (3) FIS lacks LTS-based formalization of
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,486:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: fault propagation semantics; (4) FIS does not compute multi-layer availability ceilings; (5) FIS has no AI agent
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,494:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: failure modeling capability; (6) FIS cannot perform exhaustive combinatorial scenario analysis because each
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,495:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: experiment runs against real resources with real cost and time constraints.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,496:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: A.2 Novel Contributions Summary
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,498:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: | Aspect | Present Invention | Nearest Prior Art | Distinction |
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,498:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-22 12:43:06,499:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: |--------|------------------|-------------------|-------------|
